Shields.

A shield is a defensive equipment item that absorbs damage on the player's behalf. When a shield is up, incoming bullet, projectile, melee swing, mine, bomb, time bomb, and contact damage hits the shield's strength pool instead of the player's health, with the shield's defence value subtracted from the raw damage first. The shield breaks when its strength reaches zero, leaving the player with no shield equipped until they draw another one.

Each shield lives in its own folder under the sound pack. The default shield is none, which means the player has no shield drawn and incoming damage goes straight to health.

Sound packs and info.sif files.

Shield data lives in info.sif files inside the sound pack. The full path is sounds/<pack>/main/equipments/shields/<shield>/info.sif.

Each shield has its own info.sif. The file is self contained: every stat the shield uses is written explicitly, and anything left out falls through to a sensible default.

The info.sif file does not list any sounds. The engine learns what audio a shield has by scanning the shield's own folder, matching whatever clips it finds against the names it expects (draw, wear, hit, loop, remove, break). Drop a clip in the folder and the shield plays it; remove it and the shield goes silent for that event. There is nothing to wire up by hand because the folder layout is the audio configuration.

Field reference.

Every field in info.sif uses the form key=value, one per line. Missing fields fall back to the defaults shown below.

defence (double): How much damage the shield absorbs per hit before passing the rest to the strength pool. The actual reduction is defence times three, so a defence of ten removes thirty raw damage from each incoming hit. Defaults to 0.

wear mode (int): How the shield is worn. 0 is body armor mode: pressing O puts the shield on, pressing O again takes it off, and while the shield is on the player can still move, fire, and jump as normal so the shield acts as passive protection. 1 is brace mode: holding O keeps the shield up, but while it is up the player cannot move, fire, or jump, and releasing O drops the shield and restores all three actions. Brace mode trades mobility for an active commitment to defense, body armor mode lets the player keep playing the game while protected.

weight (int): How much the shield slows the player down while drawn. Heavier shields cost movement and reaction speed. Defaults to 1.

shield strength (double): The shield's starting and maximum strength pool. The shield starts at full strength when drawn, and when this hits zero, the shield breaks and the player returns to no shield. Defaults to 100.

unlock level (double): The minimum character level required to draw this shield from the shields menu. Locked shields appear in the menu with an "(Unlocked at level X)" suffix and cannot be selected until the player levels up enough. Defaults to 1.

blockchance (int or int:bool pair): The percent chance the shield successfully catches an incoming hit, with an optional cushion sub-value that controls how much of the absorbed damage chips the shield strength. Written as blockchance=N for a plain percent chance with no cushion, blockchance=N:true to flag the shield as cushioned (a successful catch halves the damage that gets chipped from the strength pool before the defence value is subtracted, modeling padded armor or an energy field that softens the impact), or blockchance=N:false (or omitted) to leave the cushion off so the catch takes the full damage minus defence. The value is clamped to 0 through 100 on read. Defaults to 100 with cushion off, so a stock shield always catches at full damage; the default shields all ship with blockchance=80, so roughly 1 in 5 hits slips past to your health and the shield feels more like real body armor with occasional gaps.

launch type (string): What the shield fires back at the attacker as a counter-attack every time it successfully absorbs an enemy hit. Set launch type=projectile:<name> to fire the named projectile from builder/kombat/projectiles/<name>, or launch type=bomb:<name> to drop the named bomb from builder/traps/bombs/<name>. Set launch type=none (or omit the field entirely) to disable the counter-attack — the default shields all ship with the explicit launch type=none so the field is visible to authors as a starting point, and changing it to a projectile or bomb form turns the counter on. The counter-attack travels toward the attacker (whichever cardinal direction points from you to them, including up or down on 3d maps), inherits the absorbed attack's damage value as its own damage, and only triggers on enemy attacks: npc melee, npc bullets, and tts enemy attacks. Trap damage like spikes, mines, force fields, time bombs, and bombs never fires the counter-attack, even when the shield absorbs them.

x launch range (int): How far in tiles the counter-attack's projectile or bomb-drop travels along the x axis. Defaults to 0, and the default shields all ship with the explicit x launch range=0 alongside the other launch fields.
y launch range (int): How far in tiles the counter-attack travels along the y axis. Defaults to 0.
z launch range (int): How far in tiles the counter-attack travels along the z axis (height). Defaults to 0. Only consulted on 3d maps; on 2d and topdown maps the field is ignored. Setting all three ranges higher than zero gives the counter-attack a real reach; leaving them at zero with a launch type configured produces a same-tile counter-attack that lands at your feet.

launch speed (int): How fast the counter-attack's projectile moves through the air, written as milliseconds per tile of travel. Lower values mean a faster projectile. Defaults to 30, which the default shields all ship with explicitly. For a bomb launch, this doubles as the bomb's per-tick fall interval, so a slower launch speed also produces a slower-falling counter-bomb.
